 and transfigurations. Hope and uncertainty are critical affective and knowledge-related modalities of such imaginations and assume vital meanings in policing, managing, and experiencing health, illness, and well-being. This volume brings together contributions from medical anthropologists who address this theme across various medical spheres, including the pragmatics of hope and uncertainty, the techno-sphere, health management, and individual and socially distributed emotions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aCultural Anthropology. 4aEmotion. 4aHealth Care. 4aImagination. 4aMedical Practice. 4aMedicine. 4aPharmacy. 4aPublic Health. 4aSociology of Medicine. 4aUncertainty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aCultural Anthropology.  aEmotion.  aHealth Care.  aImagination.  aMedical Practice.  aMedicine.  aPharmacy.  aPublic Health.  aSociology of Medicine.  aUncertainty.1 aBech Risør, Mette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuclin, Thierry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChattoo, Sangeeta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDémolis, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoley, Rose-Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFortin, Sylvie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeest, Sjaak van der, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadolt, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHadolt, Bernhard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHei